<p>In <a href="/wiki/Sociolinguistics" title="Sociolinguistics">sociolinguistics</a>, a <b>T-V distinction</b> describes the situation wherein a <a href="/wiki/Language" title="Language">language</a> has <a href="/wiki/Grammatical_person" title="Grammatical person">second-person</a> <a href="/wiki/Pronoun" title="Pronoun">pronouns</a> that distinguish varying levels of <a href="/wiki/Politeness" title="Politeness">politeness</a>, <a href="/wiki/Social_distance" title="Social distance">social distance</a>, <a href="/wiki/Courtesy" title="Courtesy" class="mw-redirect">courtesy</a>, <a href="/wiki/Familiarity" title="Familiarity" class="mw-redirect">familiarity</a>, or <a href="/wiki/Insult" title="Insult">insult</a> toward the <a href="/wiki/Addressee" title="Addressee">addressee</a>.</p>
